      <hedline>
        <hl1>After the Second Debate, a New Scorecard</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Lincoln P Bloomfield letter on presidential debate says he wuold have expected both candidates to focus on need to rethink multilateral peackeeping so that job can be done right next time US demands UN forces be sent out (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Candidates Meet in Restrained Debate'' (front page, Oct. 12):</p>
        <p>Jim Lehrer asked the candidates what they would do about intervention in humanitarian-type conflicts. They never mentioned the answer given to the question by the last several American presidents -- ''get someone else to do it.'' Except for the use of NATO in Kosovo, the ''someone else'' has been the United Nations.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Candidates Meet in Restrained Debate'' (front page, Oct. 12):</p>
        <p>Jim Lehrer asked the candidates what they would do about intervention in humanitarian-type conflicts. They never mentioned the answer given to the question by the last several American presidents -- ''get someone else to do it.'' Except for the use of NATO in Kosovo, the ''someone else'' has been the United Nations.</p>
        <p>As both candidates compete to restrict the use of American military in peripheral situations, I would have expected them to focus on the need to rethink multilateral peacekeeping so it can do the job right the next time Washington demands that United Nations forces be sent somewhere.</p>
        <p>Mr. Bush may not know anything about peacekeeping, but Mr. Gore knows better and is responsible for depriving the public of a rare discussion of the realities of ''humanitarian intervention'' in the 21st century.  LINCOLN P. BLOOMFIELD  Cohasset, Mass., Oct. 12, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is professor emeritus of political science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</p>
      </block>
